05085nam a22007335i 9780231557467DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315574677 a10.7312/chen208502doi  a(DE-B1597)642728  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPL2933.E52675bK8513 2023 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a895.13/6223/eng/202210261 aChen, Yao-chang, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPuppet Flower :bA Novel of 1867 Formosa /cYao-chang Chen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b10 b&w figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aModern Chinese Literature from Taiwan00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Principal Characters -- t1 A Pyrrhic Victory -- t2 The Tragedy That Befell the Rover -- t3 Orphans of Mixed Blood -- t4 Identity Revealed -- t5 Repulse of the Foreign Forces -- t6 Serenity Lost and Found -- t7 Troops Marching -- t8 Puppet Mountains -- t9 Praying to Guanyin -- t10 Epilogue -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tGlossary0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1867, an American merchant ship, the Rover, sank off the coast of southern Taiwan. Fourteen sailors reached the shore, where almost all were killed by indigenous people. In retaliation, the United States launched two disastrous military operations against local tribes. Eventually, the U.S. consul to Amoy, Charles Le Gendre, negotiated a treaty with Tauketok, the chief of the eighteen tribes of the area, that secured safe passage for shipwrecked sailors.Yao-Chang Chen’s historical novel Puppet Flower retells the story of the Rover incident, bringing to light its pivotal role in Taiwanese history. Merging documented events and literary imagination, the novel vividly depicts Tauketok, Le Gendre, and other historical figures alongside the story of Butterfly, a young woman of mixed ethnic heritage who serves as an interpreter and mediator during the crisis. Chen deftly reconstructs the multiethnic and multilingual society of southern Taiwan in the second half of the nineteenth century from multiple perspectives, portraying local people’s daily struggles for survival and their interactions with Han Chinese settlers, Qing dynasty bureaucrats, and Western officials, tradesmen, and adventurers. The novel explores nineteenth-century Sino-American and Sino-indigenous relations and emphasizes the centrality of Taiwanese indigenous cultures to the island’s history.A gripping work of historical fiction, Puppet Flower is a powerful revisionist narrative of a formative moment in Taiwan’s past. It was recently adapted into a popular Taiwanese TV miniseries, Seqalu: Formosa 1867.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aBerry, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z9783111318264oZDB-23-DSP0 cprintz978023120850540uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/chen2085040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557467/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023 